column18: "Which hee knoweth because hee this examinate being then boatswaine of and in the said shipp did receive them there aboard by tale [110 elephants teeth] from the hands of the said Chatterley whoe delivered them out of his boate aboard the said shipp [the Dove] then lying at Carlisle bay in the Barbadoes, and upon receiving them this deponent entred the same in a booke by him kept for such use, which booke hee hath lately perused and findeth the number to be as aforesaid but for whoe accompt the said teeth were laden hee saith hee knoweth not and hee saith that about 83 of the said teeth were marked at the small end of every of them with one notch, and all thre st of the said teeth laden by the said Chatterly as aforesaid vidlicet about 27 thereof were marked thus [crosshatched mark], which hee knoweth because hee likewise entred the said marke in his said booke, which hee hath lately perused as aforesaid as aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.211v)

column18: "Since the comminge home ofthe said shipp from the Barbadoes this last voyage the said Chetterleys wife either came or sent to this deponent (but whether shee came orsent hee remembreth not) to enwuire of her husband, and this deponent to his best remembrance either tolde her or the messenger sent by her that hee had a token aboard his said shipp for her from her husband and being asked what it was, hee said it ws a parcell of elephants teeth, and that his boateswaine could give her notice what the quantitie thereof was" (HCA 13/61 f.209r); "Hee made a proffer of buying the elephants teeth inquestion of the said Chetterleys wife and proffered a summe of money for the same, but howe much hee remembreth not, and albeit hee made the said motion, yet hee saith hee intended with himselfe not to buy the same, and this deponent gave order to his boateswaines mate to deliver the said teeth ashore to the said Chetterley's wife" (HCA 13/61 f.309r); "And saith the schedule annexed (and nowe showne unto him) is wholly written and subscribed with the proper hand of him this deponent" (HCA 13/61 f.209r)

column18: "The said booke was and is the booke that was kept by the arlate John Amery whilest hee lived touching the golde of the company of the shipp the John arlate and some private accompts of his owne for the sayd voyage, which booke after his the said Amerys death comming to the hands of the arlate Richard Webster, hee the said Webster and Captaine Andrews brought the same to this deponent to make out the accompts touching that voyage betwixt Mr Vassall and company and the said Webster and the wife of the said Emery. And saith that hee having perused and compared diverse letters and other writings of the said Amerys with the said booke, hee findeth that the said booke is written with his the said Emeries hand, and this deponent findeth not by the said booke that there is any more gold sent or to be delivered to the arlate Cragge or any other deriving any title from him then is set downe folio 4 of the said booke whereunto hee referreth himselfe" (HCA 13/61 f.429r); "Hee this deponent hath had the keeping of the said booke ever since Webster brought the same home, till it was brought into this Court, and in all that while it hath not bin altered, and as hee beleeveth and perceiveth by the same, it hath not bin altered since his the said Amereys death" (HCA 13/61 ff.429r-429v)

column18: "On or about the nineth day of the moneth of January last past Mr John White merchant interrogate, did upon the Exchange London tender unto the foresaid Mr Nicholas Skinner to be underwritten a pollicie of assurance in the Saint Katherine of Longsound, from Plymouth to Liverpoole interrogated, which hee knoweth because hee sawe and perused the said pollicie of assurance. And saith that the said Mr Skinner having viewed the same, tould the said Mr White in this deponents presence and hearing that hee would not meddle therwith in regard of the danger of Irish men of warre on those coasts, to which hee saith the said Mr White made answer that the shipp should not stirre without Convoy, and moved and incouraged the said Mr Skinner to underwrite £200, but Mr Skinner replying that £100 was enough, and that hee would not underwrite a penny unlesse the said shippe were to goe with Convoye, the said White further said, that shee should not stirre without Convoye,  upon which the said Mr Skinner underwrote £100, whereas hee beleeveth that hee would not have underwritten a penny as himselfe said, had not the said Mr White assured him that the said shipp was to have Convoye, for hee soe farr  relyed upon the said Mr Whites promise of a Convoy, that hee forthwith gave order to this deponent being his servant assoone as hee came home to take notice in writing of the said Mr Whites said promise of Convoye, and this deponent did accordingly take notice of the same in writing, which writing hee hath nowe lately perused, and thereby the better  calleth the premisses to minde" (HCA 13/61 f.504v); "He was present at the house of the said Mr Skinner situat in Saint Nicholas Lane London at the subscription of him the said Mr Skinner" (HCA 13/61 f.504v)

column17: LADING AT VENICE: GOODS; MERCHANDIZES; LADING AT ZANT AND ZEPHALONIA: CURRANTS
column18: "In her course about the middle of July last past, entring the Channell they met with two English shipps the master of one whereof called the Barnestaple Merchant gave them notice that there were shipps revolted and told them that hee supposed they would be abroade, this deponent hearing him give the said notive" (HCA 13/61 f.235r); "The master and company of the Love having met with the said intelligence put into and touched in Plimouth Sound arriving there about the 18th day of July 1648, and being soe arrived there, their master presently sent away his purser ashore with a letter to be sent to his owners in London for advise (as hee said) where  the said Revolted shipps were and what course they should take to avoide them, their comming in thither being purposely to send for the said advice, and to intimate their said arrivall, and out of care to avoide the said Revolted shipps" (HCA 13/61 f.235r); "About a weeke after the writing and sending away the said letter, their said master received a letter in Plimouth from some of the owners in answer of his soe sent, whereby (as hee made this deponent and the rest of the company acquainted) hee was by his owners ordered that in regard the winde was westerly (as hee saith it then was) and the Revolted shipps in Holland (and soe contrary to bringe them out) hee should withall speade bringe away the said shipp for London before the Revolted shipps came back into the Downes, and withall their said master was as hee said ordered by the said letter to makke a signe at Dover and a pilot should be sent him aboard if occasion there to carry the said shipp on the back of the Goodwin Sands as is arlate" (HCA 13/61 f.235r); "The said letter and order received as aforeaid at Plymouth the master and company of the said shipp set saile with her and came and arrived in Dover Roade on the first day of August last past, and there hee saith there came two pilots aboard them from Dover, to the end (as this deponent understood ) to carry their said shipp on the back side of the Goodwin Sands, to avoide the Revolted shipsp" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); "Upon the comming of the said two pilots abord the said shipp the Love their said master in this deponents hearing moved and desired them to afford their best assistance in carrying of the said shipp on the backside of the Goodwin Sands and in keeping of her cleare from the Revolted shipps or to that effect" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); "The said master gave order to one of the said pilots to carry the said shipp on the back of the Goodwin accordingly if it might be donne" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); "Hee sent away his purser to London to intimate soe much to his said owners, this deponent seeing the said purser goe ashore to that purpose" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); "Upon the said intelligence, Captaine Rider came downe from the owners to endeavour the release of the said shipp, this deponent seeing him arrive and goe from on board the Love to goe on board the Princes shipp to that purpose, but shortly after hee came back againe and signified that hee could not prevaile by any meanes for her discharge" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); "[AST HELAND SLUCE] this deponent and diverse other of her officers assoone as her goods were delivered left her to come for London, refusing to serve under the Prince" (HCA 13/61 f.236r)

column7: Mercator [merchant]; Passenger from Barbados to London [of the Elizabeth]; Present on the ship the Elizabeth in Carlisle Bay, Barbados, when Robert Williams fell sichk and dyed
column9: Passenger from Barbados to London [of the Elizabeth]
column10: Present on the ship the Elizabeth in Carlisle Bay, Barbados, when Robert Williams fell sichk and dyed
column18: "On a day happening in or about the moneth of May last past this deponent was present on board the said shipp Elizabeth in Carlisle Baye in the Barbadoes where hee saith the said Williams laye sick of the sicknes whereof hee the night following dyed, and then and there after this deponent had moved the said Williams to make his will, and hee saying that hee had already made the same, the said Williams desired this deponent to take a booke which hee directed him unto and to write therein such things as hee should direct him, and accordingly this deponent [?reaching] the said booke, the said Williams dictated unto this deponent severall debts and engagements which hee ought in England and for adverntures that were made with him, which this deponent accordingly entred in the said booke about the middle thereof, and amongest others there was entred by his directions a hundred pounds and some odd pounds (but howe many above a hundred hee remembreth not) owing by him to Mr Sowden in Towerstreete London which the said Williams then said was for an adventure which the said Sowden had made with him the said voyage; And then and there the said Williams said that there was amongest the golde brought in the said shippe the Elizabeth from the Golde coast, golde belonging to other persons upon adverntures besides  that whoch belonged to the ffreighters of the said shipp, amongest which persons hee named Mris Judith Peele, but saith that hee doth not remember that hee therein named Mr Sowden or any other of the said persons. And at all the premisses hee saith his precontests William Coppin and James Clinket merchant and others were alsoe present" (HCA 13/61 ff.288r-288v); "Since the premisses the said shipp the Elizabeth with that booke and all other the said Williams his bookes of accompts touching the said voyage in her as alsoe the shipp the Dover arlate are safely arrived in this port of London, this deponent arriving in the said shipp the Elizabeth" (HCA 13/61 f.288v)

column18: "During the greatest part of which time hee this deponent (as hee saith) did keepe the cash and bookes of accompt of the said Robert Oxwicke untill in or about the moneth of September 1638, and did in that time receive such moneyes as were due and payable unto him the said Mr Oxwick and pay such summes of money as were oweing from him to merchants, assurers and others" (HCA 13/61 f.292v); "The particulars whereof were then (according to the custome of merchants in such cases) sett downe in writing in the said Robert Oxwicks book of assurances folio 68, in eight severall summes" (HCA 13/61 f.282v); "The said Robert Oxwick did within the time predeposed assigne over to the said Roger Corbett certaine English licenses to trade in Portugall in the time of warr, in consideration whereof it was agreed that the said Mr Corbett should pay to Mr Oxwick aforesaid 3 per cent for all English goods which hee the said Corbett should shipp for Portugall, and 3 per cent for all such goods as hee should bringe back into England, and it was further agreed betweene them that the said Corbett should pay unto the said Oxwick (for a Spanish licence which hee likewise assigned over unto the said Corbett) after the rate of 13 per cent for all such goods as  hee should import into Portugall, and to pay or cause the moneys to be paid to the said Robert Oxwick his factor in Portugall, or to himselfe here in England" (HCA 13/61 f.283r)

column18: "He this deponent was to goe and went master the said voyage in the ffrancis of London in company of the said shipp the Content in service of the said merchant freighters and was acquainted with the treaty about and concluding of the said contract and present at Mr Warmeston a scriveners when the same was by order of the said contractors put to writing" (HCA 13/61 f.519r); "Hee was present at the Swanne taverne in Limestreete together with the foresaid Mr Oxwicke Godfrey Jones and the said Mr Passfeild and Mr Arlabeer and others, and heard them in treatie together about the freightment and charter partie arlate before the same was drawne or put in writing, and therefore the said Pasfeild and Arlabeere were acquainted therewith before the signing and sealing thereof by the said Jones" (HCA 13/61 f.519v)

column17: LADING: MUSKETS; PISTOLS; WOOLLEN CLOTH; FLAX; HEMP; TOBACCO; IRON STAVES "When the said shipp was soe seized there were aboard her 337 muskets, 12 paire of [?holsters] (6 paire whereof had pistolls therein] a peece of woollen cloth, one hogshead of flax, foure packs of hemp, 6 rolles of tobaccoe, 2 hogsheads of cutt tobaccoe, and 121 staves of iron, all which goods wares and merchandizes hee saith were laden by Irish factors residing in fflannders for the accompt of and consigned to the foresaid Mr Browne and Mr Sleyland to Waterford in Ireland" (HCA 13/61 f.209v)

column18: "From the 23th daye of Aprill 1646 unto the 29th daye of June next following hee this deponent (being a lighterman imployed by the producent Robert Smith to carry beere from his brewhouse at New Crane in Wapping aboard shipps and otherwise) did receive from the said brewhouse and carry in his lighter with his contest and then servant William Allen) aboard the said shipp the Greene dragon then lying in the River of Thames and delivered aboard to her use (the said Bowden being then master of her) the quantities of 13 tonnes and one barrell of beere at 40 shillings per tonne, the time and particular quantitie hee saith hee the better remembreth because as hee received and carried the same aboard as aforesaid hee entred the same in a booke which hee lept for that use, which booke hee hath lately perused and found therein entred as aforesaid. And hee saith the said beare at such delivery thereof was the goods of the said Robert Smith and hee was the lawfull owner and proprietor thereof. And the like beere hee saith was then usually solde at that time at that rate and the sam was well worth soe much by common estimation and might soe have bin othrwise solde" [HCA 13/61 f.211r]

column18: "Upon the said notice, Captain Milner master of the said shipp the Love seemed much troubled as doubting howe hee should come with the said shipp and lading clearly for London for feare of the said Revolted shipps, and expressed much care and industrie to avoide them to which purpose this deponent heard him consult with his company, and that hee might receive advise from his owners concerning them, hee put into Plymouth, and there arrived about the time arlate, and of this deponents knowledge hee forthwith sent away a letter for London which hee said was to his owners for advise touching the said shipps" (HCA 13/61 f.259v); "About a weeke after the sending away of the said letter there came to the said master a letter from his owners in answer thereof, which (amongst other things) intimated and signified unto him that the Revolted shipps were in Holland and that hee might safely come with his said shipp for London, which they willed and ordered him forthwith to doe, as this deponent understood from some of the company of the said shipp after the receiving and reading of the said letter" (HCA 13/61 f.259v); "He likewise understood by and from some of the said shipps company upon receipt of the foresaid letter, that the owners had taken order for a pilot to come on board them at Dover, and hee beleeveth it to be true, because that the said master and company settingwith the said shipp upon the foresaid advise, and arriving in Dover roade, there were two pilotts brought on board the said shipp by Mr Tiddiman of Dover, on or about the first of August last past and upon their comming this deponent understood by the company that the said pilots were brought by order of the owners to carry the said shipp about by the back of the Goodwin sands to avoide the said Revolted shipps" (HCA 13/61 f.259v); "After their said comming onboard this deponent heard the said Captaine Millner speake to and desire them to carry the said shipp on the back side of the said sands, and to doe their utmost to avoide the said revolted shipps or to that effect and telling them withall that hee had received order from his owners to avoide the said revolyed shipps if by any meanes hee could" (HCA 13/61 f.259v) THE WIND WAS STRONG AND THE TWO PILOTS, MILLNER AND DIVERSE OF HIS COMPANY WERE NOT EXPERIENCED ENOUGH TO CARRY THE LOVE BEHIND THE GOODWIN SANDS OUT OF DANGER]; "The said master and company finding the apparant hazard they must have runn to attempt the bringing of the said shipp on the back of the said sands, by reason the winde was not aire and the said pilots found unskilfull, were constrained to come and did come with the said shipp into the Downes, hoping to have libertie to bring her up to London, but upon her comming thither shee was seized upon and stopt by the said revolted shipps , all which hee knoweth being on board her" (HCA 13/61 f.260r)

column18: "In and by the foresaid charterparty which this deponent soe heard read as aforesaid, it was further covenanted and agreed in all things to the effecte arlate, besides this deponent heard the said John Bushell by word of mouth promise and agree to and with the said Marcke Beayle upon making the said bargaine of freightment and before the same was drawne into charterpartie that hee the said Marcke should have leave to lade 3 or 4 tonne of goods aboard the said shipp the said voyage for his owne accompt freight free" (HCA 13/61 f.383v); "The said shipp was at the time arlate and is of the burthen of 240 tonnes and soe many tonnes of goods shee was and is able to carry and from Rochell to Saint Lucars in Spaine this last voyage after her going out of England shee made out 248 tonnes of this deponent's knowledge seeing the goods (beinge corne and smiths anvills) laded and discharged and taking notice thereof in writing. And saith shee was well able to have carried 240 tonnes of goods and upwards from the said Islands to this port of London the voyage in question in case the said Bushell or his assignes had laded dying wood or more woade or some other goods amongest the sugars as other merchants usually doe of his knowledge, this deponent having made severall voyages to the said Islands" (HCA 13/61 f.384r);

column18: "Within the time arlate and whilest the said shipp the Concord was and soe remained at Bourdeaux to looke for a freight, it was generally noised and reported at Bourdeaux and other places thereabouts that all the differences both in England and Ireland betweene the Parliament of England and those that were in armes against or in opporition to the same were fully agreed concluded and composed, and that there was a freedome and libertie of trade and commerce to any porte either in England or Ireland without being subiect or liable to be taken or surprisedby any man of warr on either part, and to that purpose there was a letter imported to the said Peter Elinge, which this deponent sawe and heard the same read" (HCA 13/61 f.364v); "The said rumour or reporte of the said agreement being soe firmely and generally and in soe credible and confident a manner averred and noised abroade and the said Peter Elinge in further confirmation of the truth thereof having seene a letter of advise hee said Elinge after hee had staide and sought for a freight at Bourdeaux for the space of three monethes or thereabouts as aforesaid did accept of a freight for the said shipp from Bourdeaux for Waterford in Ireland (as hee saith another master of a shippe did upon confidence of the truth of the said report)" (HCA 13/61 ff.364v-365r)

column18: "Out of their care to avoide them they put into Plymouth sound to get advice concerning them and being arrived there their master presently wrote and sent away to London to his owners to certifie them of their arrivall there and to receive advice from them where the Revolted shipps were, and what course they then should take to that effect, this deponent being tolde of the contents of the said letter to that purpose" (HCA 13/61 f.238r); "It was on or about the 18th day of July 1648 that they soe arrived in Plymouth sound" (HCA 13/61 f.238r); "About a weeke after the sending away the said letter to the owners for London, there came an expresse from them by which (as their master informed them) hee wa advised that the said Revolted shipps were in Holland and that hee was ordered in regard the wind was westerly and faire (as hee saith it was) to come away and bringe up the said shipp for London with all speade before the said Revolted shipps come back againe into the Downes, and further that hee should stand in at Dover and put out a west, for they would there appoint a pilot to come on board to carry the said shipp about by the backside of the Goodwin Sands if occasion were or to that effect" (HCA 13/61 f.238r); "According to and upon the said order and directions from the owners, the master and company set saile with the said shipp from Plymouth and came and arrived in Dover Roade on or about the first day of August last, where there came two pilots aboard her by order (as both they and Mr Tiddiman that brought them said) of the owners or some of them to guide and conduct the said shipp the best course they could to avoide meeting with the said Revolted shipps and to bring her to that end (if occasion were) on the back side of the Goodwin Dandsm this deponent hearing both them and the said Mr Tiddiman declare soe much on board to their master" (HCA 13/61 f.238r); "When the said master found and perceived that hee could not by any meanes by him used get the said shipp and lading cleered, hee sent up Mr Hendra his purser for London to signify soe much to the owners, thsi deponenty seeing the said purser soe sent away" (HCA 13/61 f.238v); "Upon the said notice, the said owners sent downe Captaine Rider into the Downes to endeavour the release of the said shipp and lading, whoe there arrived of this deponents sight and went aboard the shipp where the Prince was to that purpose" (HCA 13/61 ff.238v-239r); "As hee heard the said Captaine Rider (though hee used all the meanes hee could possibly) could not procure the discharge of the said shipp, but saith that there were diverse gentlemen and officers by commannd from the Prince (as they themselves said) put on board the said shipp the Love for the more sure looking to her and keeping her there" (HCA 13/61 f.239r); "The master and company of the Love could not possibly finde any opportunitie of making an escape with the said shipp while they were under the said power and restraint, so strictly were they guarded and narrowly watched by the said revolted shipps, and at thhe departure of the said revolted shipps out of the Downes, they inforced and constrained the master and company of the Love to carry her alonge with them together with her lading to Helvard sluce and there shee was detained, this deponent being still in her" (HCA 13/61 f.239r); "After such time as the said shipp the Love came and arrived to Helbard sluce aforesaid, the master did againe repaire unto the Prince to petition and make meanes for her release and discharge and of her lading, and that hee did as this deponent understood by order from his owners, and when hee could not get her discharged, hee made meanes and sent unto him for leave for the bringing of her into the sluce as being unfitt for service, and thereupon there were by order of the Prince or his officers, some men sent aboard to viewe her touching such her inserviceablenesm and this deponent went from place to place with them on board to showe them howe that the boltspritt was crackt, the head of the foremast crackt and alsoe the foretopmast and fore yard, all the foure shrowds decayed and unserviceable and the mainemast defective and badd the mainetopsaile yard broken and gonne all her standards loose and broke, with many other particular defects and insufficiencies, but when their said master could neither get her released, nor leave to carry her into the sluce, this deponent and diverse others of the cheife officers and mariners after the goods were delivered got their master to cleare them, which hee freely did, and soe they left the said shipp to come for London, refusing to serve in any imployment under the Prince" (HCA 13/61 f.239r); "Hee is very well acquainted with the handwritinge of their said master Gregory Millner, and verily beleeveth the schedule arlate to be wholly written and subscribed by him" (HCA 13/61 f.239r); "This deponent heard the said Thomas Tiddiman (whom hee hath knowne for theise five yeeres last past and upwards) upon his bringing the said pilots aboard tell their master that hee had order from the said owners to bringe them, and heard him reade a letter (which hee said hee had received from them) being of the tenor of the second schedule mentioned in the 29th article aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.239r)

column18: "[SPEAKING OF A LICENSE AT ALBOZINE TO LADE WHEAT FOR CADIZ INTO THE TALBOTT] Which he knoweth for that hee understood soe much by a Jew that was their spokesman and messenger that went every daye to and gaine betweeene the said shipp and the shore of Albozine and brought word to the effect here deposed" (HCA 13/61 f.22v); "After such time as the said Hwkins had soe taken and surprized the said Turkish shipp and her lading of corne, videlicet on the said Satterday in the afternoone, the Alcade or Governour arlate sent and wrote unto their master  Joseph Blowe commannder of the said shipp the Talbott to wish and desire him to sende unto the said Hawkins to request him to deliver back agine or surrender up the said Algiers shipp and her lading of corne soe by him taken and surprized, which hee this deponent knoweth because hee sawe the said letter brought on board the said shipp the Talbott to their said master and ws by him made acquainted that the contentes thereof was to the effect by him deposed" (HCA 13/61 f.23r); "The Alcade sent their master word to their said shipp that if hee could procure Captaine Hawkins to make restitucon of the said Algier shipp soe by him takena and crried away together with her company and lading, his men soe surprized and imprisoned should be retourned to him without other ransome, otherwise that they should not be redeemed without money" (HCA 13/61 ff.24r-24v)
column19: "[SPEAKING OF A LICENSE AT ALBOZINE TO LADE WHEAT FOR CADIZ INTO THE TALBOTT] Which he knoweth for that hee understood soe much by a Jew that was their spokesman and messenger that went every daye to and gaine betweeene the said shipp and the shore of Albozine and brought word to the effect here deposed" (HCA 13/61 f.22v); "They hadJew on board when they went with the said shipp to the porte of Albozine aforesaid whoe went on shoare nd treated and traded for them at Albozine aforesaid with the Alcade there for ladeing for the said shipp and hee the said Jew was one of the persons seized upon by the Moores" (HCA 13/61 f.24r); "Hee this respondent for his part  heard before that they must have hostages at Albozine for their Jew whoe was to be their interpreter, or els the Moores were likely to seize him and keee him prisoner till hee should be rnsomed, and to that purpose when they arrived there they had two Moores brought on board in hostage for the said Jewe, but the men that were soe seized went on shore without hostages and unarmedl but hee saith that they rode within commannd at Cales upon thei rfirst retourne thither without the men, and brought their said shipp in the rode before Cales within commannd of the towne before their master came to any treaty with the merchants about the redempcon of his men soe taken and imprisoned as aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.24v)

column18: "Hee this rendent after the said shipp the Guift was surprized  was carried and examined upon oath before the maior of Pensance and his confession put into writinge as hee conceived (fr hee cannot write) and whereas in the first schedule anned it is said that they came out of Corke river on the d of October past, it is true, but they were forced in againe by contrary winde and soe came not thence and proceeded on the said voyage till the 14th of the same moneth, and arrived at Rochell about the 19th daye of the same moneth, and whereas it is said therein they repaired from Rochell to [?Shattow] and there tooke in the rest of their lading, hee saith that Shattowe is within five or six miles of Saint Martins and standing upon Saint Martins river and when any goods are ther laden, they used to saye the amongest sea men that hath come from Saint Martins as being the principall place upon the said river, and saith they tooke in all their said lading at Shattowe neere Saint Martins, saving  fewe pease for the shipps provision and about two tonne and a halfe of wheate which they before had taken in at Rochell, and saving in theise particulars hee saith the contents of the said schedule are true and soe donne as therein is contayned" (HCA 13/61 f.353r); "The marke thereunto subscribed or made hee saith was donne with this examinates hand" (HCA 13/61 f.353r)

column18: "The said master (Mr George Millner) presently sent away a letter for London to his owners this deponent seeing the purser goe ashore about sending of it away, and giving them notice of their arrivall, and desiring to knowe what course they should take in respect of the said revolted shipps, that being as hee heard the effect of the said letter" (HCA 13/61 f.236v); "About a week after the sending away of the said letter, their said master received another letter from the owners in answer thereof, but the contents thereof hee did not heare, only hee heard their said master saye that hee could not learne any otherwise but that the said Revolted shipps were then at Heland Sluce" (HCA 13/61 f.236v); "Upon the foresaid letter soe received from the owners, and the said common report that the said Revolted ffleete was gonne out of the Downes the master and company of the Love set saile from Plymouth and arrived with her in Dover roade (but the time of such their arrivall hee remembreth not) where hee saith there came two pilotts abord them from Dover, this deponent seeing them come on board" (HCA 13/61 f.236v); "Hee did not heare any of the discourse betwixt their said master and the said pilotts" (HCA 13/61 f.237v); "Hee remembreth not howe the winde then was, and saving the carrying their said shipp on the back side of the Goodwin Sands could not have bin attempted without apparant hazard and danger of the losse both of shipp and goods without a very able and experienced pilot, for this deponent heard their company on board saye that none of them had ever gonne that waye, and aving hee remembreth it was then very fowle weather and that the winde blewe hard" (HCA 13/61 f.236v); "When their said master could not get his said shipp and lading cleared hee sent his purser Mr Hendra away to London to acquaint his owners therewith, this deponent seeing him soe sent away" (HCA 237r); "Upon the said notice given to the owners, there came a gentleman downe from them into the Downes, and came and called their master aboard to goe wuth him to the Prince about aking meanes for the release of the said shipp, and forthwith went aboard the Princes shipp to that purpose, this deponent seeing him soe arrive and goe on board the said shipp" (HCA 13/61 f.237r); "The said gentleman soe sent downe could not (as it appeared) get the said shipp released, but saith there were diverse officers and gentlemen put on board her by order as they said of the Prince and his Counsell to secure her" (HCA 13/61 f.237r); [AFTER MILLNER FAILED REPEATEDLY TO GET THE LOVE CLEARED] Hee [Millner] cleered any of his men that desired it, and soe diverse of her cheife officers and mariners to the number of sixteene or thereabouts (whereof this deponent was one) left her to come to London" (HCA 13/61 f.237r); "The number of the said gentlemen and offficers soe put on board the said shipp the Love to guard and watch her as aforesaid was about 60, whoe continued on board her untill her bringing to Helward sluce aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.237v)

column18: "After the said shipp the Love had taken in the foresaid currans and other lading the master and company of her brought her and her lading towards this kingdome of England, intending to come therewith to this porte of London, and in her said course about the middle of July last past entring the Channell mett with the shipp the Barnstable Merchant, the master whereof gave them notice that there were shipps revolted, and that it was supposed they would be then abroad or to that effect, this deponent hearing him speake thereof...The said master and company haveing received the said notice did put into the Sound of Plymouth out of care and desire to avoide the said Revolted shipps, and arriving there on or about the 18th day of July last their said master Gregory Millner forthwith wrote a letter to his owners being in London to certifie them of his arrivall there with the said shipp, and desired to receive suddaine advice from them where the Revolted shipps were and what course hee should take to avoide them or to that effecte, with the contents of which letter this deponent was made acquainted by their purser Mr Hendra his contest, this deponent helping to carry him ashore therewith at Plymouth the same daye they there arrived, and hee going to send it forthwith away for London" (HCA 13/61 f.229v); "After the premisses and while they continued at Plimouth in expectation of an answer of the said letter, there came a letter in answer thereof about 8 dayes after the sending of that of their masters, wherein and whereby the owners aforesaid wished and ordered the said master to bringe the said shipp forthwith for London in regard the winde was then westerly and faire (as indeede hee saith it was) and being soe westerly was not fitt to bringe out the said Revolted shipps, and to bring her away before the Revolted shipps came up into the Downes, or to that effect, this deponent hearing the said letter read aboard the said shipp in the porte of Plymouth by their said master, the same being written as hee remembreth from Captaine Rider in the name of the owners" (HCA 13/61 f.229v); "Thomas Tiddiman of Dover came aboard them neere Dover roade and brought the said pilots aboard, and this deponent heard him saye aboard to their master that the owners had written to him to provide and bring them a pilote aboard to carry their said shipp in a course for London soe as shee might not meete with the Revolted ships or to that purpose" (HCA 13/61 f.231r)

column18: "The said master and company out of their care and desire to avoide the said revolted shippe, did put into and touch in the Sound of Plymouth and there arrived about the eighteenth day of July last past, and forthwith upon their arrivall there, their master (Gregory Millner) wrote and sent up a letter to his owners here in London to receiove advise from them touching the said Revolted shipps and what course they should take, this deponent being made acquainted with the contents thereof to the effect aforesaid by their said master" (HCA 13/62 f.233v); "They staying at Plymouth for answer of the said letter, there came about a weeke after the same was sent away an answer thereof, wherein (as their master acquainted the company) the said owners wrote that they should make haste and bringe the said shipp and lading for London, for that the Revolted shipps were gone out of the Downes to the northward or to that effect" (HCA 13/61 ff.233v-234r); "There came two pilots on board the said shipp from Dover, this deponent seeing them soe come on board...for hee heard not what was said betwixt them and the master and company touching the matters arlate" (HCA 13/61 f.234r); "Upon the premisses there came a merchant downe from the owners to endeavour the release of the said shipp and lading, this deponent seeing him come aboard the said shipp and goe on board the shipp wherein the Prince was to that purpose" (HCA 13/61 f.234r); "After the said shipp came and arrived neere Helvard sluce the said master went againe aboard the Princes shipp, and this deponent heard him saye that hee went by order of his owners to make meanes for the release of the said shipp the Love and her goods and lading aboard her, and that if hee could not obtaine it, hee would if hee could get leave to goe with her into Helvard sluce as not being serviceable" (HCA 13/61 ff.234r-234v); "According to the said directions of the owners (intimated as aforesaid) to the company by their master) the said shipp the Love set saile from Plymouth and arrived in or neere Dover Roade on the first of August last past" (HCA 13/61 f.234r);

column18: "About eight monethes after they were soe entred into the service of the said State of Venice in the said shipp the America, and were ready to enter into fight with the Turkes the said Grayson endeavoured to dishearten the company of the said shipp (shee being then in the harbour of the Isle of Melo)  from fighting with the Turkes, telling them openly in the shipp and with much earnestness that if they gott any wounds or hurts in the said fight hee would not helpe or care them, unlesse they would first give him a note under their hands to pay him for the  care soe much as hee should thinke fitt, and that otherwise they should lie and wallowe in their owne blood, and persih, and some of them hee said (which hee named not) should perish like the untimely fruite of a woman, or hee then or there used words to the same effect the premisses hee knoweth being present at the speaking of it" (HCA 13/61 f.36v)

column17: LADING AT CHICHESTER: MALT "The mault in question was not measured at the lading therof on board the said barque in the presence of the said Lange or any of his company, but saith the same was brought in carts a mile or thereabouts from Chichester to Saltmill and there putt into boates, and thnce carried in boates about two miles before it was put aboard the barke, in which space none of the company of the said barque had the charge of the same or were present to oversee it, but saith the same was put into the said barque next wayes out of the sacks without any measuring thereof of this deponent's sight" (HCA 13/61 f.391r)
column19: "The mault in question was not measured at the lading therof on board the said barque in the presence of the said Lange or any of his company, but saith the same was brought in carts a mile or thereabouts from Chichester to Saltmill and there putt into boates, and thnce carried in boates about two miles before it was put aboard the barke, in which space none of the company of the said barque had the charge of the same or were present to oversee it, but saith the same was put into the said barque next wayes out of the sacks without any measuring thereof of this deponent's sight" (HCA 13/61 f.391r); "During such tyme as the said corne was in lading and putting on board the said barque this deponent seeing the sacks of a boates loade thereof somwhat slackly filled, and suspecting the measure, went to the said Mr Exton to his house in Chichester and tolde him it was fitt they should have a bushell on board to measure the said corne or such sacks thereof as they thought good and desired him they might have a bushell to that purpose, but saith the said Mr Exton put him off, and told him they neede not doubt of their measure or to that effect..." (HCA 13/61 f.391r); "After the said lading of the said corne the said Lange sett saile with the said vessell and came towards London and here unladed and discharged the same to him the said Exton and his assignes by measure of such a bushell as hee the said Exton produced, to the number of 200 quarters and a halfe quarter of mault, this deponent seeing a greate part therof soe measured and delivered in the presence of him the said Mr Exton whoe scored up the number of quarters at such delivery thereof" (HCA 13/61 f.391r); "The said mault at the time of delivery thereof into the said barque was not skreened but fowle and dustie and this deponent hath since the premisses herard the said Exton acknowledge that the same was not then skreened and saith mault unskreened delivered on board any shipp at the place aforesaid or thereabouts will at the time of the delivery thereof out againe at London abate and fall short of the measure it was delivered. And therefore it is usuall and accustomed for merchants that lade the same to allowe for wast a quarter in the skore, for soe much or thereabouts unskreened corne doth usually fall short not withstanding the care and diligence of the master and company" (HCA 13/61 f.391v); "The said Mr Exton said that there were 11 score quarters of malt laded on board the said barque" (HCA 13/61 f.391v)

column17: LADING AT SUTA: WHEAT; PLANNED LADING AT ALBOZINE: CORN "Within the time arlate the Talbott did departe and sett sayle from the foresaid Rode of Suta and arrived in the Baye or Rode of Albozine arlate, and after her arrivall there, the master and company of her had free license and leave from the Alcada or Governour there to receive and take on board the said shipp her lading of wheate, and to carry the same whether they pleased, and to that purpose there ws ordertaken in the countrey thereabouts for asmuch wheate for her lading as could reasonably and well be stowed in her" (HCA 13/61 f.30v); "That (as hee was credibly informed) there was a full lading of wheate provided for the said shipp the Talbott at Albozine and hee saith that in a former voyage (shortly before) shee had carried and made out eight thousand hannocks of wheate or neare thereabouts from Galisia in Spaine to Suta aforesaid of this deponents knowledge helping to lade and unlade the same, and being informed by the boatswaine that it was the quantitie here deposed, and se much shee might have taken in at Albozine and carried for Cales, had shee not bin soe hindered by the occasion of the said Hawkins in such his taking of the said Algiers shipp, for every of which hannocks the said ffowell, Dickens, and company were to have had and received (as this deponent heard the said master and company say) the number of three rialls of plate per hannock" (HCA 13/61 f.31v)
column19: "On the Satturday aforesaid after the said Hawkins had taken and surprized the said Turkish shipp and her lading, the Alcade or Governour at Albozine did send a letter unto their said master on board the said shipp the Talbott, this deponent seeing the letter soe brought, and hee saith hee heard their master after it was read, say that it was to the effect arlate, and that night hee saith their said master sent his skiffe and his mate John Cade this deponents contest on board the said Hawkins, and this deponent was informed that his going was to the effect menconed in the said eleaventh article: And hee saith that upon the retourne of the said John Cade hee this deponent heard him say that the said Hawkins refused to release or deliver up the said Turkish shipp and lading, but that hee had told him, that what hee had donne in taking her hee would answer in England or to that effect" (HCA 13/61 f.31v)

column18: "The arlate John Wilkinson arrived in the Downes with his shipp the Debora on the tenth day of Aprill last past and staid there about two houres, in which space the said Wilkinson went ashore to Deale with intent as hee said to enquire at the Posthouse if there were any letters of advice or instructions for him from the arlate Harrison and Edwards or either of them, which hee knoweth for that hee this deponent was then aboard being one of the said shipp's company, videlicet carpenter of the said shipp and keeping a journall of their voyage hee the better knoweth the certaine day of such their coming into the Downes, and when the said Wilkinson retourned againe on board the said shipp, hee said hee could [?meddle] with noe letters or instructions from the said persons (which hee said hee expected in answer of letters by him written to them from Plymouth) and thereupon (the winde being faire)  hee sett saile to goe with the said shipp and her lading of salt from the Downes to Dansike" (HCA 13/61 f.215r)

column18: "About Whitsuntide last past was a twelvemoneth and after the said Thomas Gosling the elder his death, and when his said sonne was preparing to goe out with the said shipp, this deponent being the relict of the said Thomas Goslinge the elder, and desirous to have his accompts with the owners cleared, having received the first schedule lilate of Mr Greene for such goods taken up by her said husband for the said shipps use, this deponent endeavoured a meeting amongest the said owners, that soe her husbands accompts might be stated, and procured Mr Lee a merchant for his brother a part owner livinge at Rotterdam, and Mr Andrewes of Ipswich for his brother another owner, and Mr Church an owner and also the arlate Alderman Witham another owner to meete at his the said Alderman Witham his house in Aldermanbury, and then and there this deponent made them acquainted with the first schedule lilate touching the delivery of the goods therein mentioned and showed the same unto them" (HCA 13/61 f.131r)

column9: Purser [of the Greenfeild]
column18: "Hee this deponent hath well knowne the arlate Henry Powell as alsoe the shipp the Greenfeild articulate for all the time arlate and saith that for all the said time the said Henry Powell was and is master, commannder and governour of the said shipp the Greenfeild and was soe constituted by and with the consent of the owners thereof, which hee saith hee knoweth to be true, because hee this deponent hath bin purser of the said shipp for most part of the said time, and hath kept the shipp's booke and accompts, and was present at severall meetings where the most part of the said owners have bin present and appointed and constituted the said Henry Powell master of the said shipp" (HCA 13/61 f.186r); "In the yeare 1642 arlate the said shippe the Greenfeild did want and stand in neede of diverse provisions, materialls and necessaries for the fitting or furnishing of her to sea upon her then intended voyage, which hee knoweth belonging then unto her and being purser of her as aforesaid, and the said Powell did by the order and approbation of the said owners provide provisions, materialls and necessaries as were fitting and convenient for the furnishing and fitting out of the said shipp to sea, this deponent drawing up the bills for the said provisions as in the booke of accompts exhibited and nowe showne unto him appeareth, and being present and seeing David Goubard for Mr Curteene, William Greene, Edmund Beane, Captaine Powell, ffrancis Tryon and Thomas Hamble owners firme and subscribe to the originall booke of accompts whereof this exhibited hee saith is a copie allowing the said disbursements, most part of which  provisions, materialls and necessaries this deponent sawe brought aboard and imployed to the said shipp's use" (HCA 13/61 f.186r); "The same is a true copie of the originall booke of accompts kept by this deponent as purser aforesaid (which said originall hee hath nowe likewise with them) of the charges, expenses and disbursements made the said voyage by the said Captaine Powell for the use of the said shipp from the said 8th of September 1642 (inclusive) to the said 8th of July 1645 inclusive...For hee saith hee left the said shipp at Zant within a day or two after the said 8th of July 1645" (HCA 13/61 f.186v); "The said William Courteene Esquire had in his hands at the time arlate for freight received upon a former voyage of the said shipp more then his proportion the summe of £280, this deponent being present when the said accompts were made up before the shipp's going to sea upon the voyage in question, which said summe was by agreement of the said Goubard for Mr Courteene, charged upon Mr Courteen's said fourth part of the said shipp, as appeareth by the lesser booke of accompts exhibited fol. 15, to which hee referreth himselfe." (HCA 13/61 f.186v); "Hee this deponent kept the said shipp's accounts aswell for the receipts as aforesaid, all which accompts were under this deponent's owne hand writing, and this examinate hath the same with him nowe at his examination" (HCA 13/61 f.187r)

column18: "The said John Baker was whilest hee lived commonly accompted owner and proprietor of the other moietie or half part of the said hoy and her tackle and furniture, and was master and governour of her and soe commonly accompted, for this deponent hath knowne the said Baker in his life time to make up his accompts as master and halfe owner thereof, to the said Thomas Hallum, whilest hee lived, and since to the producent his executrix" (HCA 13/61 f.82r); "Within the time arlate the said John Baker did make severall voyages with the said hoy and traded betwixt this port of London and Burneham in Essex and some places in Kent, and as by his accompts, which hee hath made to the said producent appeareth (which accompts this deponent hath lately seene and perused) hee hath received severall freights and earned severall summes of money within the said time, videlicet from the third of September 1646 to the 16th of June 1647, hee earned and received the summe of £11 - 10 pence of lawfull English money, and from the said 16th of June to the 30th  of October 1647, the summe of £10 of like money, the one halfe of which summs was and is due unto the said Margaret Hallum, as owner of the said halfe part"  (HCA 13/61 f.82r); "Within the time libellate videlicet in the moneth of October last past or somewhat before, the said Margaret Hallum at the instance of the said John Baker did by his contest William Hallum the producent's servant and other of her servants deliver or cause to be delivered to and for the provision of the said hoy all and singular the goods and commodities mentioned and expressed in the first schedule arlate whereof shee was then lawfull owner and proprieterix, this deponent being made acquainted with the delivery of all or the most part of the said goods and provisions, and hee saith hee sawe some of them spent and eaten aboard the said hoy" (HCA 13/61 f.82r); "It appeareth likewise by the accompts of the said John Baker given to the producent in his life time, that hee received aboard the said hoy all and singualr the goods, wares and merchandizes mentioned and expressed in the said second schedule for the accompt of the said Margaret and to be by him solde and disposed of for the best benefitt and advantage of the said Margaret Hallum, and that hee disposed thereof and dolde the same accordingly" (HCA 13/61 ff.82r-82v); "At the time of delivery and taking aboard of the said goods provisions and commodities predeposed of, they were worth the severall summes of money mentioned and expressed in the said schedules, and for soe much the same might then have bin solde and at the rates the same were then commonly solde of this deponent's knowledge, being a wholesale cheesemonger and a freeman of his trade and thereby well acquainted with the prices of such commodities" (HCA 13/61 f.82v); "During all the time aforesaid the said Margaret Hallum paid and satisfied the said John Baker for the repairng, victualling, provision and all other charges that were or grewe due upon her halfe part of the said hoy, over and besides the goods and provisions delivered as aforesaid as appeareth by the said John Baker's said accompts under his owne hand" (HCA 13/61 f.82v); "The said John Baker in his lifetime and about a moneth before his death did make up his accompts with the said producent, and saith there were not any other dealings, debts, accompts or reckonings betweene them as concerned the said hoy and which did arise and proceede by reason thereof and of the voyage and imployment of the same" (HCA 13/61 f.82v)

column19: "The voyage in question videlicet about two yeares and three quarters since the shipp the John and Isaack arlate riding at anchor without the barr of Calabarr, the arlate John Bernardo ffalcon with his shipp arlate came to an anchor neare unto the place where the said shipp the John and Isaack ridd, and the said ffalcon came with his boate on board their said shipp the John and Isaack, hee himselfe steering the boate as coson thereof and foure negroes rowing him, and comming on board the said ffalcon pretended himselfe to be a subiect of the Kinge of Portugall and pretended that the said shippe the Nostra Seniora belonged to Portugall...The premisses hee deposeth and knoweth to be true becaue hee this deponent went the said voyage in the said shipp the John and Isaac and was coxon on board her, and sawe the said ffalcon soe come on board and heard him speake to the effect aforesaid, this deponent partly understanding his language. And for that the said ffalcon proved afterwards to be a Spaniard and that his shipp belonged to Spain" (HCA 13/61 ff.68r-68v)

column17: LADING AT SUTA: WHEAT; PLANNED LADING AT ALBOZINE: CORN "Hee was informed on board both by the said master and a merchant on bord that was imployed upon the said designe by the said fraighters, whoe likewise informed him that the said merchanst had agreed to paye the said master the summe of three rialls and a halfe per hanncok for every hannock of wheate that the said shipp should receive and take on bord her at Albozine aforesaid and deliver out againe at the port of Cales, and most commonly a greater rate is paid as sometimes foure rialls, sometimes five and dometymes more per hannock, but in regard the shipp thee Talbott was there at Suta, within the mouth of the Streights and by that meanes soe convenient to goe for Albozine the agreement was made at soe easie a rate as hee hath predeposed" (HC 13/61 f.25r)
column18: "Which hee knoweth because hee this deponent was then on board (being chirurgeon in the said shipp) and heard the Jew that was their drugger man or agent to goe on shore, bring his reports and notes of his bargaine from the said Governour to their master on board this deponent being intreated  by the master to heare and receive the said Jewes reportes and notes because hee this deponent could speake Spanish, which language the said Jewe used with them and in which his notes and particulars of his agreements with the Governour were written" (HCA 13/61 f.25r); "[AFTER THE SEIZURE OF 17 OF THE TALBOTT'S COMPANY] The same day the Governour having first caused a white cloth to be hunge out on shore, sent a Jew on board them with a letter to their master signifying that hee had caused the said company to be seized and imprisoned, because an English man (meaning the said Hawkins) had soe surprized and carried away the said Algiers ship betwixt whom and the English as hee said there was peace and amitie, and desired in the said letter that by the bearer the name of that English man and of his shipp might be sent him, that hee might intimate it to Algier that soe they might seeke for remedy or to that effect, and the said letter further purported that the said  men should not be released nor the they suffered to take in any more corne unlesse the said Turkish shipp with her lading and company were first restored which hee knoweth because hee this deponent read the said letter And thereuppon their said master Mr Blowe caused a letter to be written back to the said Governour, wherein hee expostulated the falte and fowle dealing of him the said Governour in causing his men to be surprized after hee had ingaged his promise and gvien them some other securitie for their free libertie to trade with him for the said corne, and sent the same to him by the said Jew, this deponent alsoe reading the said letter before it was sent, and on the next day the said Governour sent another letter to their master in answer thereof purporting that in case the said Turkish shipp with her men and lading were delivered up againe hee should have his men sett at  libertie otherwise that they should not be released unlesse satisfaction were first made to the valew both of the said Turkish shipp and lading and of her men, which answer was by the Jew that brought it after his hanging out a cloth at shore laid downe on the sands, and that letter this deponent alsoe read, being of the contents by him here deposed, and soe they were constrained to depart away with only a small part of their lading of wheate (the precise number of hannocks hee remembreth not) to the greate losse of the said Dickons, ffowell, Willson and Company owners of the said shipp" (HCA 13/61 f.25r)
column19: "Which hee knoweth because hee this deponent was then on board (being chirurgeon in the said shipp) and heard the Jew that was their drugger man or agent to goe on shore, bring his reports and notes of his brgaine from the said Governour to their master on board this deponent being intreated  by the master to heare and receive the said Jewes reportes and notes because hee this deponent could speake Spanish, which language the said Jewe used with them and in which his notes and particulars of his agreements with the Governour were written" (HCA 13/61 f.25r)

column17: LADING AT VENICE: GOODS; MERCHANDIZES; LADING AT ZANT AND ZEPHALONIA: CURRANTS "The said shipp the Love did remaine and abide in the porte of Venice and there received and tooke on board her diverse parcells of goods and merchandizes for the use and accompt of severall English merchants to be brought to and for this porte of London and afterwards went and sailed therewith to Zant and Zephalonia and there tooke in the remainder of her lading in currans for the use and accompt of the foresaid Mr Massam, Mr Robinson, Mr Man, Mr Collier and company and other merchants of London and here to be delivered to them and their assignes, this deponent seeing them laden and takinge an accompt thereof" (HCA 13/61 f.240r)
column18: "The said shipp the Love did remaine and abide in the porte of Venice and there received and tooke on board her diverse parcells of goods and merchandizes for the use and accompt of severall English merchants to be brought to and for this porte of London and afterwards went and sailed therewith to Zant and Zephalonia and there tooke in the remainder of her lading in currans for the use and accompt of the foresaid Mr Massam, Mr Robinson, Mr Man, Mr Collier and company and other merchants of London and here to be delivered to them and their assignes, this deponent seeing them laden and takinge an accompt thereof" (HCA 13/61 f.240r); "The said master and company of the Love having received such notice and intelligence, out of their care and desire to avoide the said revolted shipps, did put into and touch in the Sound of Plymouth and there arrived about the eighteeneth  day of July 1648, and after their arrivall their said master and this deponent sent up a letter for London subscribed by them both and directed to one of their owners and to be communicated to the rest, to certifie them of their arrivall there and to desire advise from them where the Revolted Shipps were and what course they then should take or to that effect, which letter this deponent carried ashore at Plymouth and sent it away assoone as hee could for London" (HCA 13/61 f.240r); "Upon the foresaid letter soe sent as aforesaid the owners writt another letter backe againe to their said master and this deponent (which they received about a weeke after the sending away of theirs as aforesaid) and therein did advise them that the said Revolted shipps were in Holland" (HCA 13/61 f.240r)

column18: "There was a written paper inclosed in an old almanack on board the said shipp soe taken at the time of her seizure, which paper (as this deponent heard the same read on board) conteyned to this effect In the name of God Amen I sett saile from under Bel Isle (and then was sett downe a day and moneth which this rendent hath forgotten) my course west norwestly and some other papers were found on board, but hee remembreath not their tenor, only that they did not concerne the vessell, and saith that hee this rendent lately had and hee beleeveth hee still hath the said first paper at home" (HCA 13/61 f.150v); "Hee this deponent hath well knowne the arlate Captaine William ffishman the space of neere two yeares last past or thereabouts and for about a yeare and halfe of that time this deponent hath served in the shipp the Adventure (whereof the said ffishman was captaine) as gunner on board her and hath gone diverse voyages in her in that time and hath sundry times seene a Commission which the said Captaien ffishman had to sett forth and equipp his said shipp in a warlike manner to the effecte arlate which the said ffishman said was accordinge to an Ordinance or Ordinances of Parliament" (HCA 13/61 f.149v); "This rendent did not read or peruse the said Commission" (HCA 13/61 f.150r)

column18: "All the foresayd moneyes and the goods soe bought in the Downes were solde bartered, disposed and changed by the said Robert Williams in his life time in Ginney and Binney aforesaid, and the retourne and proceede of the same and the books and accompts by him kept concerning the said voyage were laden and put aboard the said shipp the Elizabeth, all which hee knoweth, because hee being with his said master there, sawe the same soe donne as hee hath predeposed, and kept the accompts thereof" (HCA 13/61 f.224r); "Since the arrivall of the said shipp Elizabeth in this porte of London videlicet in or about December last past hee this deponent was present at the Shipp Taverne in Bishopsgate streete did there see the arlate Peele and Vincent and foure or five more of their company and sawe there severall of the said Williams his bookes of accompts and writings concerning the said voyage, and there they were examining and casting up the same, this deponent then looking into and knowing the said bookes, and they the said Peale and Vincent and others to or for their uses have had and received all or the greatest part of the golde, elephants teeth and othergoods ware and merchandiszes arlate, this deponent seeing the greatest part therof delivered unto them and theire use" (HCA 13/61 f.224r)

column10: Delivered goods from ffranics Prichard's ropeyard in Saint Olaves Southwark to the Margaret Adventure
column18: "This deponent on the behalfe of the producent ffrancis Prichard, did at his said Prichard's rope yard at Horsey downe in the parish of Saint Olaves aforesaid deliver on the 29th of December 1645 to the use of the said shipp the Merchant Adventure one cable weighing 25 hundred weights and a halfe hundred and thirteene pounds weight, also on the 20th of January 1645 one leaden lyne, also 16th of July 1646 two peeces of rope weighing 200 and 3 pounds weight, and in the same day one coyle of spunn yarne, also 23th of July aforesaid one white passing rope of fine yarne weighing two hundred and fourteene pounds weight. Item 24 of July aforesaid one coyle of ratlyne weighing a quarterne of a hundred and 4 pounds weight, and six pounds of marlyne, and 3 of August 1646 one paire of ties. All which said goods were by him delivered the times and place aforesaid to the use of the said shippe by this deponent they being then the goods of the producent ffrancis Prichard whoe was lawfull owner of them and were delivered some of them to the said Goslinge himselfe master of the said shipp, some to his boatswaine and other of his men, sent by him to receive them, and were delivered at the prices mentioned in the said schedule, which hee knoweth for that this deponent upon such his delivery of them did enter or cause them to be entred in their day booke, which hee hath lately oerused and findeth the same to agree with the said schedule touching those particulars deliverd. And at the times of the delivery thereof the same were worth the severall and respective prices and summes sett downe in the said schedule to the said particulars of this deponents knowledge and the like were then soe commonly solde" (HCA 13/61 f.54r)

column18: "She well knewe the sayd shipp the Desire and well knoweth that Mr John Clarcke dwellinge in Birchinge Lane London was owner of a sixteenth part of the sayd shipp, tackle and furniture at the tyme of her departure to sea on her last voyage to the Barbadoes and that the sayd Clarcke had a bill of sale of a sixteenth part of the sayd shipp made unto him by her sayd husband. And the sayd Clarcke sent forth some serges in the sayd shipp in her sayd last voyage. The premisses she knoweth to be true for that she hath seene her husband's booke of accompts, and hath for the use of her husband received some moneys from the sayd Mr Clerke as owner of a sixteenth part of the sayd shipp since her departure to sea on her last voyage wherin shee was cast away (as shee hath heard) in her passage from Antego to Virginia" (HCA 13/61 f.445v)

column19: "The arlate Richard Williams was in the time arlate and when the worke and goods schedulate were done and delivered, lawfull owner and proprietor of all the said goods and soe commonly accompted" (HCA 13/61 f.110v); "Hee this deponent was journeyman and foreman of the shopp to the producent Richard Williams when the worke schedulate was donne and when the goods mentioned in the said schedule were delivered, and saith that within the time libellate videlicet in the space of halfe a yeere or thereabouts of that time happening in the yeare 1646 the said Richard Williams did by himselfe and servants and at the instance of the arlate John Bowden doe all the worke and deliver all the iron ware and goods mentioned in the said schedule in both leaves thereof to and for the use of the said shipp the Greene Dragon towards her fitting up and setting out to sea, this deponent helping to deliver most of the said goods and to doe most of the said worke, and being made acquainted with all of it at the time the same was delivered and donne, all which goods hee saith were delivered and worke done at the said Richard Williams his shopp neere Dick shore in Limehouse and according to the direction of the said John Bowden master of the said shipp [the Greene Dragon], which this deponent heard him give, which Bowden hee saith came diverse times to their said shopp while the said goods were in delivering and worke in doing to give order thereabouts and for the sending the same aboard the said shipp...This deponent kept reckoning of most of the said goods upon a talley kept for that purpose, and what hee did not thereupon, was hee saith donne by the said Richard Williams or others of the shipp, and with his this deponent's notice and knowledge, working in the said shopp and seeing the same donne" (HCA 13/61 f.110v);

column17: LADING AT FALMOUTH: PILCHARDS "Hee did lately very well knowe the shipp the Anne of ffalmouth interrogated whereof one Thomas Chaldwish (sic) (who hee likewise well knewe in his life time) was master. And saith the interrogated Mr Jones and Mr Browne were commonly accompted owners of the said shipp, tackle and furniture, which said Mr Jones and Mr Browne hee saith at the said shipps departure from ffalmouth (which was on or about the first day of December 1645), did lade and put on board the said shipp to the number of betweene a hundred and nyntie and two hundred hogsheads of pilchards to be carried from thence to the Canaryes, which were soe laden shortly before such departure of the said shipp from ffalmouth, and were accordingly carried to the Canaries and there delivered, which hee knoweth to be true because hee this examinate as factor to the said Mr Jones and Mr Browne [THE OWNERS OF THE ANNE OF FFALMOUTH] did deliver them on their behalfe in the Canaries, whither hee passed in the said shipp when the said goods were transported" (HCA 13/61 f.57v)

column17: LADING AT WEENES NEAR KIRCADY: SCOTCH COALS "In one of the monethes arlate tempus aliter non recolit the shipp ffortune arlate of this deponents sight and knowledge tooke in her ladinge of Scotch coles at Weenes near Kircady arlate wherewith she wass loaden by the arlate ffrancis Hogge the then master of her and his company to goe from Kirccady in Scotland to Camphere in Zealand which hee deposeth for that he was present aboard the said shipp the ffortune when she was loden with coles and did helpe amongest others to bringe the said shipp out of the harbour to goe forward in her said intended voyage and sayeth that there were noe more coales loaden aboard the said shipp as he verily beleeveth then wht was then laden aboard her and payed for by the said ffrancis Hogge and Company owners of the said shipp but wht the valewe of the said coales or how much they were then worth he cannot depose" (HCA 13/61 f.177v)

column7: Gentleman
column18: "[DEPOSING IN THE ADMIRALTY COURT ON JANUARY 23RD 1648/49] In the moneth of November 1647 hee first heard of the losse of the shipp the Marigold interrogate, first by way of rumor (and knoweth not by or of whome hee heard the said rumour) and afterwards in the said moneth hee heard it more certainely in the company of one Mr [?Hawlings], John Birdseie and Richard [?Cray] at his the said Crayes house at the White Beare at Wappinge, and heard it of them, but whether hee had any notice at all of the said losse on or before the sixt day of the said moneth of November 1647 hee remembreth not, but beleeveth it was after the said sixth day that hee first heard any thinge thereof" (HCA 13/61 f.243v); "Hee deposeth that on the 13th of November 1647 hee accidentally mett with the interrogate Mris Beale in the shoppe of the foresaid John Birdseye at Wapping Wall, and understanding her to be the wife of Simon Beale whoe had made some assurance upon the said shipp the Marigold, this examinate asked her whether there were ought ensured for her husband upon the said shipp, and shee answered that there was assurance made thereupon for her husband, and then this examinate askeing her when shee had notice of the losse of the said shipp, shee tolde him shee had newes thereof on the fourth day of the said moneth" (HCA 13/61 f.243v)

column7: Gentleman; Clerk of the Office of Assurance London
column8: Gentleman; Clerk of the Office of Assurance London
column18: "In the moneth of January or end of December 1648 or thereabouts there was a pollicie of assurance drawne up in the Registers Office for the Court of Assurance by his contest John Chase one of the clerks of the said office for the assuring Shershaw Cary and company in the Saint Catherine of Longsound (Eerick Peterson master) from Plymouth to Liverpoole, which hee knoweth because hee sawe and perused the said pollicie after it was soe drawen up" (HCA 13/61 f.503v); "The interrogate Mr John White caused the said pollicie or writing of assurance to be soe drawne up, and gave order for the same, which said Mr White hee saith sollicited the said assurance and pollicie and procuring the same for and on the behalfe of the said Mr Shershaw Cary and company, which hee knoweth because hee this deponent was moved and imployed by him the said White to procure the same to be underwritten by some of the assurers" (HCA 13/61 f.503v); "The said Mr White affirmed and declared to this examinate in the Registers Office of the Court of Assurance London that the said shipp the Katherine of Longsound was at Plymouth and safe and that shee was to goe the voyage in question (and for which the said pollicie or writing was drawne) with a convoy to Liverpoole, and that Mr Carey had treaty or was in treaty with some man of warr to convoy the said shipp the Katherine to Liverpoole the voyage in question" (HCA 13/61 f.503v); "Hee this deponent being soe spoken to and imployed by the said Mr White to procure the said pollicie to be subscribed by some of the assurers on the behalfe of the said Cary and Company, hee presented the same accordingly unto diverse of them to be by them underwritten, telling them (as the said Mr White had informed him) that the said shipp the said voyage to Liverpoole was to have convoy, but they obiected the danger of the voyage in regard of Irish men of warre that were about that coast, howbeit upon the mention of a convoy they  the more willingly subscribed as to this deponent appeared. And hee beleeveth the said Mr White was present in the office when hee this deponent presented the said pollicie and moved the underwriting thereof by diverse of the assurers" (HCA 13/61 f.504r); "Hee was present at the underwriting of the said pollicie by Mr Bigge, Mr Gould, Mr Torrold, Mr Polsted, Mr Gareland, Mr Webster and diverse others of the assurers, and that the  time of such their underwriting therein mentioned, which was soe donne in the office aforesaid, but whoe in particular were present besides, hee saith hee remembreth not, there being diverse comming in and going out" (HCA 13/61 f.504r); "Hee beleeveth that soe many of the said assurers had underwritten the said pollicie before this deponent heard any speech of or about any convoy for the said shipp the said voyage, as their subscriptions amounted (to his best remembrance) unto the summe of sixteene or seaventeene hundred pounds or thereabouts, but whoe they were by name hee doth not nowe remember and the rest hee beleeveth subscribed after such declaration and speech of convoy" (HCA 13/61 f.504r); "It is an usuall and ordinary thinge when a shipp is aggreed upon and warranted to goe with convoy, to put the same downe by way of memorandum under the pollicie of assurance, and the reason why such memorandum is not sett downe in the pollicie in question, is because the said Mr White did not really warrant that the said shipp should have Convoy the said voyage in question" (HCA 13/61 f.504r)

And saith it was before the sixth day of the said moneth of November last that hee was soe certified by letter of the losse of the said shipp, And otherwise hee saith hee cannot answer, saving that to his best remembrance tHE said letter was brought unto him by the porter of the poste of Ipswich aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.208r); "Hee knoweth not of any letter sent unto or received by the arlate Mrs Little intimatinge the losse of the said shipp, and saith the contents of his said letter soe received from Mr fforth soe farr forth as concerned the said shipp was that Richard Little's shipp was suncke or lost or to that effect, saying hee doth not otherwise remember either the contents of the said letter or the said business, it being soe longe since donne and soe little concerning him, that hee had noe occasion to beare it in not much" (HCA 13/61 f.208v)

column18: "Hee this examinate first heard of the losse of the shipp the Marigold interrogate on the third or fourth day of November 1647, on which day hee received a letter to that purpose from Mr John fforth of Ipswich, sent to him this examinateThe said letter beares date the second of the said November" (HCA 13/61 f.232v); "Hee neither made nor procured any such policie of ensurance as is arlate to be made, and saith that the contents of his said letter touching the said shipp were that shee was cast away" (HCA 13/61 f.232v); "Within the same short time after his receipt of the said letter the said Mrs Little (understanding that this examinate had some advise concerneing the said shipp) sent to him by her maide to send her the said letter, but saith that hee wrote a note there out of his letter (which was that shee was cast away) and sent it her, but howe many dayes this was after hee had notice thereof hee saith hee cannot by any measnes call to minde" (HCA 13/61 f.232v); "The next day after hee received the said letter hee made the contents thereof touching the losse of the said shipp knowne to severall persons, but hee remembreth not any one of them by name, or whether any of them were owners of the said shipp or not...He showed the said letter to [?Mr] Truelove, but whether before or after the sixth of November hee remembreth not" (HCA 13/61 f.232v)
