column17: LADING AT SUTA: WHEAT; PLANNED LADING AT ALBOZINE: CORN "Within the time aforesaid after the foresaid merchants had soe taken the said shipp the Talbott to fraight, the said shipp the Talbot did sett sayle and depart from the harbour of Suta aforesaid and rrived neere the porte of Albozine arlate, and hee saith tht being there arrived, and the master and company having procured license and authoritie from the Governour of that place to receive and take on board the said ship her lading of wheate to be transported as is arlate, there was by the merchants and others provdided many hannocks of wheate to be putt on board the said shipp the Talbott of this deponents sight and knowledge whoe did there help to stowe the same" (HCA 13/61 f.20v); "At Suta aforesaid the merchants that tooke the shipp the Talbott to fraight as aforesaid did promise to provide her a full lading of corne at Albozine, and hee saith shee was well able to carry and make out eight thousand hannocks of wheate, for soe much and somewhat more shee brought from Galisia to Suta aforesaid, and soe muchshee might have taken in at Albozine in case shee had not bin hindred as aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.21v)
column18: "In the eveninge of the same on which the said Hawkins and Company in the shipp the Charles aforesaid had soe taken the said Algier shipp being on a  Saturday, their master Mr Blowe after a request or message sent unto him from the said Governour to the effect arlate, did send his mate John Cade and George Rayner the boatswaine in his boate from  the said shipp the Talbott t the said Thoms Hawkins to wish and desire him to deliver up the said Algier shipp and her lding soe as before surprized, and hee saith that afterwards when the said John Cde was retourned hee this deponent on board heard both him and the boatswaine say that the said Hawkins notwithstanding their said nessage refused to deliver up the said Algier shipp and her lading, but said that what hee had donne, hee would answer for in England, and soe carried away the said Algir shipp and her lading with him" (HCA 13/61 f.21r)
column19: "[RETURNING FROM CADIZ TO ALBOZINE TO REDEEM 17 MEN OF THE TALBOTT'S COMPANY WHO HAD BEEN TAKEN PRISONER] The said master sent a Spaniard (whom they brought from Cales) in a boate to shore to mediate and sollicite for the relese of their men and for leave to take corne on bord their said shipp the said Spaniard being one that could speake the Moriscoe language, whoe having donne his errnd (as hee said hee had) retourned againe to the said shipp the Talbott and tolde the sid master that the Governour would not suffer them to take in any more corne there, but sid hee might redeeme his company which were imprizoned with money, otherwise they should not be relesed or to that effect, and to that end wished him to goe baout with his shipp to a castle in custody of the Spaniards called Pinyoon, which was distant thense bout foure leagues, and said that the men should be sent thither if hee meant to redeeme them, And thereupon hee saith that the said master and company with the said shipp the Talbott aforesaid went towards the said castle and arrived before the [?XXXX] (and this hee saith wwas about six weekes after the taking of the said Turkish shipp by the sid Hwkins as aforesaid) and finding that there ws noe other meanes to release the said men, the sid master out of such moneys s hee had belonging to the sid owners and some that hee borrowed of the company did really and truelly pay and disburse for the redemption of the said mariners (as this deponentw as informed on bord and verily beleeveth) after the rate of sixtie peeces of eight for the rescue of each man of 14 of those that were soe surprized, one of the company soe restrained being dead and two others being exchanged for two Morres that they had on board, which summe amounts in all to much about the summe and number of 800 peeces of eight s this deponent estimateth the same" (HCA 13/61 ff.21v-22r)

column17: LADING AT CHICHESTER: MALT "Mr Exton at the lading of the said mault said that it contayned the quantitie of 220 quarters of mault" (HCA 13/61 f.388r); "Within the time arlate the said Nicholas Exton did hire and take to freight the said barque the Abigael of and from the said Robert Longe to carry and transport mault from the port of Chichester to this port of London or to Newcastle, as the said Exton should appoint upon meeting the said Longe with the said barque at Gravesend and which hee promised to doe, and hee the said Exton did promise and agree to and with him the said Longe to pay unto him the summe of twelve pounds ten shillings (lawfull money) and a barrell of beere of eight shillings for the carrying and transporting of 200 quarters of mault in the said vessell the voyage aforesaid at the delivery thereof, and after that rate for every quarter of mault that the said barque should carry more then the said 200 quarters, all which this deponent knoweth because hee this deponent was present in the house of one Mr Harwood (as hee remembreth his name to be) being an inn in Chichester together with the said Exton and Longe when they met about the said freightment, and heard the same concluded on and agreed on betweene them in all particulars as hee hath predeposed" (HCA 13/61 f.387r)

column18: "On a day happening about Shrovetide last was a twelvemoneth there was a meeting at this deponent's house situat on Towerhill betweene the arlate Thomas Marsh his sonne (being his the said Thomas his mate in the shipp the Deliverance arlate) and all or the most part of the mariners belonging to the said shipp whose names are schedulated, and there being some discourse about the wages due to the said mariners, the said Marsh the younger produced his booke wherein their wages were entred according to the rate for which his father had hired them, and showed the same to this deponent, which this deponent read and found the same wages per moneth as are schedulated to be therein set downe as due to each of the said persons schedulated, and the said Marsh the younger confessed that those were the wages agreed with them for by his father and that they had served in the said shipp for all the times in the said schedule expressed, and the said William Marsh confessed the same was written with his hand by direction of his father master of the said shipp, and that hee kept the shipp's booke for his said father" (HCA 13/61 ff.534v-535r); "Hee perusing the said booke twice, the time and place aforesaid remembered and brought away by Hart the particular names of the mariners and summes monethly due them and for howe longe served in all things as in the same schedule is sett downe hee being withall well acquainted with all the said mariners at that time" (HCA 13/61 f.535r)

column17: LADING AT MADEIRA: WINES; HORSES; ASSES; GOATS "The said shipp in the said voyage to the Barbados arriving at the Island of Madera, there was there laden and put on board her for the accompt of the interrogate Henry Hall and partners 130 pipes of wine, to be delivered for their accompt at the Barbados aforesaid, which hee saith cost on the said Island of Madera tenn Milres per pipe, each milres valewing about 12 shillings 6 pence English money. Alsoe tenn cowes, which alsoe cost a milre a peece, and were taken on board at Saint Jago at Cape de Verd and one yonge horse or colt (the cost or valew wherof hee remembreth not) more 26 asses worth asnd which cost a milres per peece, and 20 goates valewing about 16 pence per peece, all put on board at Cape Verd aforesaid, but what goods were taken on board for the accompt of the said Hall and partners at the Barbadas hee saith hee knoweth not" (HCA 13/61 ff.505v-506r); "Each of the foresaid pipes of wine were at the Barbadas solde for 1000 weight of tobacco per pipe. each weight there worth 16 shillings 8 pence, but what the said cowes, horses and goates there yeelded hee remembreth not" (HCA 13/61 f.506r)

column17: LADING AT NEWCASTLE: COALS "Within the foresaid time videlicet about this time two yeeres, this deponent was present in the house of Thomas Reade situat in Newcastle aforesaid) factor for the arlate Humphrey Nicholson, and did then and there heare the arlate John Bull master of the foresaid shipp speake to and agree with the said Reade as factor for the said Mr Nicholson to lade his said shipp with coales, and the said Reade in this deponents presence and hearing did yeeld to lade him with coales for the accompt of the said Mr Nicholson, and tolde the said Ball that hee should pay the said Mr Nicholson at London for the same, which the said Ball agreed to doe, and accordingly the said Mr  Reade delivered to the said Ball (and which were put abord the said shipp) sixteene keeles of coales of this deponents sight and knowledge, amounting to seaventie pounds sterling, this deponent seeing the same put aboard the said shipp" (HCA 13/61 f.185r)

column17: LADING AT BARBADOS; COTTON; TOBACCO "In or about the moneth of October 1645 hee this deponent was present in the arlate Captaine Parr's storehouse at the Indian bridge in Barbadoes, and speaking with him of the freight of the shipp arlate, heard him the said Parr saye that hee had taken only 10 sixteenth parts and noe more of the said shipp the Dolphin to freight and the freight due from the said Captaine Parr for the said voyage did amount unto 390 and odd to be paid as is arlate, which hee knoweth because hee sawe the bill of exchange made and signed by the said Captaine Parr for the payment of the said money to Captaine Hobland dwelling in London and for which there were cottons and tobaccoes made over and assigned unto him the said Holland by the said Parr" (HCA 13/61 f.268r)
column18: "Which hee knoweth because hee sawe the bill of exchange made and signed by the said Captaine Parr for the payment of the said money to Captaine Hobland dwelling in London and for which there were cottons and tobaccoes made over and assigned unto him the said Holland by the said Parr" (HCA 13/61 f.268r); "The arlate Richard Bishopp in the Barbadoes in or about the moneth of August 1646 showed unto him this deponent letters of administration of the goods of the arlate Walter Ewans then dead, grannted unto him by the Gouvernour at the Barbadoes which said Ewans, as this deponent was informed by his said Ewans his mates dyed in the voyage in question before the retourne of the said shipp from Ginney to the Barbadoes" (HCA 13/61 f.268r); "The said Bishopp was factor or agent for the owners of the said shipp the Dolphin the voyage in question, which hee knoweth seeing him act for them there, and take upon him to dispose of the governement of the said shipp, and saith that amongest the foresaid writings soe by him delivered to this deponent to be brought for England to the owners there were diverse letters and writings concerning the said voyage directed to the said owners and an accompt of his proceedings concerning the freight and affaires of the said shipp directed as aforesaid since hee tooke the letters of administration arlate, acquainting them also thereby with the said agreement, all which this deponent found by the said writings which the said Bishop read unto him as aforesaid, which writings hee saith were cast away with the said shipp" (HCA 13/61 ff.268v-269r)

column17: LADING AT LONDON: INDIGO "The fourtie five barrells of indicoe cost the said Mr Shute £2430 - 7 shillings = 3 pence as by the said bookes and papers appeareth, and as hee remembers were reputed a greate pennyworth at that rate, and therefore they were (as hee conceiveth) well worth soe much at the time arlate, and it was commonly talked that hee would get much by them upon vending of them againe" (HCA 13/61 f.505r)
column18: "Which hee knoweth because hee this deponent being then servant to the said Mr Shute and keeping his cash found entred in his booke the payment for the said indicoe to the East India company of whom they were bought and there acquittances thereupon, and this deponent was imployed in the lading of them on board the said shipp to be transported for Holland, and hath lately perused the bookes and papers concerning the same and therefore the better calleth the premisses to mind" (HCA 13/61 f.505r); "The fourtie five barrells of indicoe cost the said Mr Shute £2430 - 7 shillings = 3 pence as by the said bookes and papers appeareth, and as hee remembers were reputed a greate pennyworth at that rate, and therefore they were (as hee conceiveth) well worth soe much at the time arlate, and it was commonly talked that hee would get much by them upon vending of them againe" (HCA 13/61 f.505r)

column17: LADING AT NEWFOUNDLAND: FISH "The said shipp the John and Ambrose at such time as shee went from Newfoundland with her foresaid lading of fish, departed thense about 20 tonnes dead fraigted, and soe many tonnes more shee could have carried of Newfoundland fish in case the said factor or agents or the said Stanley would have laden and putt the same on board of this deponents knowledge" (HCA 13/61 f.55v)
column18: "After such time as the said factor had laden and put on board the said shipp in Newfoundland the foresaid fish, the said Church their master asked him at Trinity harbour aforesaid if hee had any more fish to lade, telling him if hee had, hee the said master would take it on board, but the said Bradley answered and in this deponents presense and hearing tolde the master that hee had noe more to lade, and thereupon the said Church the master did there make a protest against the said merchant Mr Stanley or his factor for not fully lading his said shipp, this deponent being present and setting his hand to the same" (HCA 13/55v)

column19: "As this deponent often heard him say in or about the moneth of October last was two yeares, and the said Tyler then lodging at this deponent's then mistres [Amy Wilkinson] the producent's house in Ratcliffe this deponent saw him at two severall times tell and carry out £31, which hee said was to pay the said Mr Grove towards the said shipp" (HCA 13/61 f.208r); "Within the time arlate and after hee had soe bought the said shipp Mr Tyler did hire and imploye diverse carpenters and calkers to worke upon her to make her fitt to proceede to sea, this deponent seeing them sundry times at worke upon her as shee then laye at Mr Aldridge his key at the Armitage at Wapping, and seeing him borrowe severall summes of money of the producent to pay the said worke men and for materaills, £10 whereof this deponent by his directions and on his behalfe paid to the  to the said Mr Aldridge for stuffe and materialls used about the said shipp in such her reparation...She hath often heard him the said Tyler saye that the said shipp had cost him 180 and odd pounds" (HCA 13/61 f.208r); "Which this deponent knoweth to be true for that shee being then her servant and much trusted by her was by her said mistres made acquainted with and was present at the delivering and lending unto him of that said summe [of £50] at severall times in her said mistres her house in Ratcliffe and delivering to him £10 thereof her selfe by her mistres order when hee came one morning in has for the same to pay his workemen for worke upon the said shipp, and her mistres not beinge then up, and other £10 of the said money soe lent this deponent paid as aforesaid  to the said Mr Aldridge his directions and on his behalfe paid" (HCA 13/61 f.208r)

column18: "The said schedule was and is the originall bill of bottomrie made by and from the said Mare to the said James Love for the saumme faforesai, and was and is wholly written with the proper hand of this deponent being a scrivener and imployed about the drawing thereof. And hee saith that on or about the sixth day of March 1646 hee this deponentw as present and did see the arlate John Mare subscribe his name thereto with his owne hand, and seale and for his act and deede delivere the said schedule or bill of bottomrie, which was soe donne at a cookes house knowne by the signe of the Pewter Platter in Gracious Streete, then and there being alsoe present his contest Thomas Woodward and Hugh Mackinney, whoe all did sett their names thereto as witnesses of the said sealing and delivery, and by his name there appearing hee knoweth the same to be the same bill of bottomrie that was then and there soe sealed and delivered, howbeit hee saith that by the error of this deponent the dtae of the said schedule or bil is mistaken touching the yeare of our Lord, and written 1647 in stead of 1646, for hee well knoweth that it was March last was twelve moneth wherein the same was soe sealed and delivered" (HCA 13/61 f.92r)

column18: "The commission and all the papers in the latten box nowe particularly shewed unto him were in his sayd shipp when she was taken by the sayd ship the Hector, and sayeth therre were not any other writings comissions instructions charter parties coquettes or bills of lading abord the sayd shipp when she was taken, nor any throwen over bord nor otherwise disposed of" (HCA 13/61 f.471r); "Hee this deponent and two others of his company were examined before the Magistrats of Yarmouth, and that the first of the examinations annexed to the interrogatoryes is the deposition of him this deponent taken before the sayd magistrats of Yarmouth, and is subscribed with the proper hand writinge of him this deponent, and the contents therof are true" (HCA 13/61 f.471v); "The paper written in Dutch, beinge the second schedule annexed to these interrogatoryes was in this deponents chest abord the shipp in question, when she was taken by the Hector, and this deponent did receive the same in the moneth of May 1648 and acted accordinge to the directions and instructions contayned in the sayd schedule soe longe as he went in the sayd shipp called the Princess Amelia, but when he lefte the shippe those instructions became voyd, and he was not to observe and followe the same in his voyage in which he was taken, but was to acte accordinge to the newe instructions in the boxe aforesayd nowe shewed unto him, dated the tenth of Aprill 1649" (HCA 13/61 f.471v)

column18: "The Instructions given to this rendent for seizinge of shipps of Dublyn (beinge the second schedule interrate) nowe shewed unto him, were not in the same boxe and in the same place of his shippe when she was seized where his Commission and other writings were, neither were the sayd Instructions hidd in any part of the sayd shipp but were in his cheste. And this rendent when his Commissiona nd other writings were founde did tell the Captayne and company of the Hector that those were all the writings he had, but denyeth that he or any of his company did hide or conceale the sayd Instructions, but gave the key of his chest to the sayd Captayne Stokes to looke if there were any more writings, but how longe after the takinge of the sayd shipp by the Hector he knoweth not" (HCA 13/61 ff.474r-474v); "For his part he knoweth of noe paper or writinge taken out of the cheste or boxe of the interrate [?Mittee part] by the chirurgeon or any other before or after the takinge of the sayd shipp, neither doh he knowe of any writinge throwen overbord" (HCA 13/61 f.474v)
column19: "He knoweth not the name of the partye who had plundred the sayd Wittee parts shipp, but as the sayd Wittee art tould him, he which plundred his shipp spake both English and Dutch, but most English, but wheither he ws an Englishman or a Dutchman or of what country he hath not heard neither would he tell his name to the Wittee part (as the sayd Wittee part affirmed) or wheither he had or pretended to have any Commission" (HCA 13/61 f.474v)

column18: "Hee this deponent was at the taking and seizure of the shipp the Saint Olave interrogate and saith that the interrogate Henry Johnson, Gabriel Perine and Moosten Dirrickson being of the said shipp's company were after such her seizur carried by this deponent (by order of Anthonie Younge captaine of the shipp the Dragon that tooke her) into Penryn interrogated to be examined, and there hee saith they were examined and upon their oaths before Mr Dewstoe Mayor of Penryn and Thomas Melhish one of the Justices there and their confessions delivered upon their oath were there taken in writing according to what they there delivered and confessed to them, and they all subscribed the same in testimony of the truth thereof, the said Johnson and Dirrickson setting their markes and the said Perine his name therto, and then the same was attested by the said Mayor and Justice at Penryn. All which hee knoweth to be true because hee this deponent was present on the last day of January last at the swearinge and examininge of the said Johnson, Perine and Dirrickson, and sawe their examinations taken in writing and subscribed by them and attested as aforesaid, in the presence of the said Mr Melhinsh in Penryn aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.290v)

column18: "Hee this deponent well knoweth the arlate William Scott, and soe hath donne for theise nyne yeeres last past or thereabouts, and saith that for the space of a yeere last past or thereabouts this deponent and the said Scott have held constant correspondense each with each other by letters in a mercahndizing way, and saith that in the moneth of April last past hee this deponent received a letter from the said William Scott from Roane written and signed by and with his owne hand (which this deponent well knoweth) directed into him this deponent, and bearing date the 25th of the said moneth of Aprill last past (newe style) and therein the said Scott wrote unto this deponent to take ensuranse here upon the corne laden or to be laden aboard the Saint George of Hamborough, burthen 90 lasts wherof was master John Peterson Gryp, from Avray in Bretagne to Exeter or Newhaven, and accordingly this deponent here in London caused the same to be ensured to the summe of sixe hundred pounds which ensuranse was soe made on the 25th daye of Aprill last past olde style; And hee further saith that upon a second order from the said Scott hee added two hundred pounds more to the said former ensuranse on the third day of May last past old style" (HCA 13/61 f.89r); "The said Scott in his said first letter did write unto this deponent that the said corne was to be laden in the name of Mervin, meaning (as hee this deponent conceiveth) Jean Mervin one of the parties in this sute, whom this deponnt likewise knoweth, and therefore this deponent beleeveth the said John Mervin had a part in the said corne" (HCA 13/61 f.89r); "The said William Scott is a Hollander and soe reputed, and was borne at Harlaem in Holland as this deponent hath bin credibly informed, this deponent being very well acquainted with his brother a Hollander nowe living at Amsterdam, and the arlate John Mervin is accompted an Englishman, borne at Exeter" (HCA 13/61 f.89r); "The said William Scott liveth at Roane, and keepeth a family there, and there hee hath bin settled with his family about tenn monethes last past, or thereabouts, it being soe longe since they went from Kew in Surrey, where they formerly lived, and the asaid Scott went about two or three monethes before thither to settle, and to provide for the comming of his family" (HCA 13/61 f.89r)

column18: "[AT THE ENTRANCE TO THE CHANNEL MR WITHERIDGE, MASTER OF THE BARNESTABLE MARCHANT, CAME ON BOARD THE LOVE TO SPEAK TO GREGORY MILLNER] this deponent hearing the said notice given" (HCA 13/61 f.225r); "Sent up a letter to one of the owners here in London certifying their arrival there and desiring to receive advise from the owners where the Revolted shipps were and what course they should take, or to that effect, which hee knoweth being then aboard the said shipp in Plymmouth Sound, and being by the said master made acquainted with the contents of the said letter" (HCA 13/61 f.225r); "The said master received a letter from London from the said owners in answer of his soe sent, wherein (as the said master acquainted this examinate) the said owners advised him that the Revolted shipps were gonne for Holland, and therefore willed him to bringe her for London, in regard the winde was faire and westerly (as hee saith it then was) and in that the winde beinge soe westerly it was not fitt to bringe out the said revolted shipps from Holland, and willing the said master with all speede to bringe her for London before the recolted shipps came backe into the Downes, ordering him withall that as hee passed Dover hee should make a signe for that there they woudl appoint an able pilot to come aboard and cary the said shipp about the backe of the Goodwin Sands if occasion were, or to that effect" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); "Hee as credibly informed that the revolted shipps were not then come into the Downes, and hee afterwards heard that they came not in thither in eight or tenn days space after the said letter sent and answer received" (HCA 13/61 f.235v); [CHIRURGEON REFERS TO RIDER'S LETTER AS "THE ADVICE RECEIVED BY THE MASTER FROM THE OWNERS"]; "The said master upon discourse with and examination of the said pilotts, found them (as hee declared to the company) that they were not fitt and able to carry the said shipp on the backe of the Goodwin as was desired, and soe much this deponent (whoe is well acquainted with sea affaires having used the same theise 8 yeares and upwards) perceived by them, insomuch that they could not attempt the carrying her that was without apparant danger and hazard of loosing both shipp and lading, it being a busines not to bee undertaken but by experienced and able pilots" (HCA 13/61 f.226r); "When the said shipp the Love was soe staide and seized in the Downes as aforesaid together with he lading their said master went aboard the shipp where the Prince was in the Downes, with purpose as hee made this deponent and others of the company acquainted to desire and make sute to the Prince to the effect arlate" (HCA 13/61 f.226r); "Sent up his purser Thomas Hendra this deponents contest to London here to acquainte the owners arlate therewith this deponent knowing of and being privy to such his sending and knoweing that he errand was to he effect aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.226v); "Upon the said notice and intelligence, the said owners sent a merchant (whose name hee remembreth not) downe into the Downes to endeavour to release the said shipp and lading, this deponent seeing him upon such his comming and understanding from him the effect of his errand as aforesaid...during the staye of the said merchant hee consulted with the said master and company howe they might finde an opportunitye to escape with the said shipp, which hee saith was endeavoured accordingly" (HCA 13/61 f.226v); "After the said shipp the Love was soe come and arrived to Helfor sluce their said master (according to order which of this deponents knowledge hee received from the said owners repaired againe to the Prince and sued and endeavoured for release of the said shipp and lading, this deponent being once aboard the Princes shipp with him when hee went about and endeavoured the same" (HCA 13/61 f.227r)" (HCA 13/61 ff.226v-227r); [UNLIKE MANY OF THE OTHER OFFICERS, THE CHIRURGEON AND THE MASTER STAYED ON THE LOVE AND WERE THERE WHEN THE PARLIAMENTS FLEET CAME TO THE SLUCE TO ATTACK THE REVOLTED SHIPS. MILLNER DELIBERATELY PUT HIS SHIP OUT OF TRIM AND RAN HER AGROUND, WHICH THE CHUIIRURGEON WITNESSED]; "The said shipp standing in neede of ballast to saile her with, and without which hee saith shee could not come home, the said master went ashore to procure some ballast, and was there mett withall and taken by some of the mariners and others belonging to the Revolted shipps and by them staid and imprisoned for suffering the said shipp to be taken by the Lord Admiralls ffleete, and for not comming into the Sluce according to commannd as aforesaid, which this deponent knoweth because hee went ashore with him, and sawe him soe staied and imprisoned, and heard him threatened by Prince Rupert that hee should bee hanged for betraying his shipp to the Lord Admiralls ffleete" (HCA 13/61 f.227v); "Hee this deponent is very well acquainted with the hand writinge of the arlate Gregory Milner their master, having served in the said shipp all the time that hee the said Milner hath bin master of her which hath bin for three yeeres and a halfe last past or thereabouts, and having oftentimes seene him write letters and other writings in that space, and subscribe his name to many writings, and many times hee and this deponent have written in each others presense and compared their hands together, and for theise reasins this deponent is confident and almost assured that the said schedule is the proper hand writinge of the said Milner, and beleeveth the same to be the same letter soe by him sent from the Downes unto the owners here, and by this deponent before deposed of" (HCA 13/61 f.228r)

column18: "After the said shipp had taken in her lading of currans and other goods and was in her course for this kingdome, shee met with two English shipps about the middle of July last entring the Channell, the masters whereof came on board the Love and acquainted Captaine Millner (master of her) and company that there were shipps revolted and they understood they were then abroade, upon which notice the said Captaine expresst much discontent and sorowe, and advised with his mates what course hee were best to take to avoide the said Revolted shipps, and after some consultation together they resolved (although hee saith the winde was then very faire to bringe her for the Downes) to put into and did put into the sound of Plymouth to get advice from their owners what course they should take in regard the said revolted shipps were said to be abroade, this deponent being privie to and acquainted with such their discourse and expressions of care to avoide the said Revolted Shipps, and being arrived soe at Plymouth the said Captaine Millner with the first opportunitie wrote to his owners for London for advise touching the premisses and sent the letter forthwith away for London, this deponent seeing the said letter written and sealed up in a packet and soe sent away, and being by the said Captaine made acquainted that the contents thereof were to the effect aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.260v); "About eight or tenn dayes after the sending away of the said letter, the said Captaine Millner received a letter from the said owners in answer thereof, wherein as the said Captaine informed this deponent, the owners ordered him to come immediately away with the said shipp and lading for London, and that as this deponent likewise understood they would send pilots aboard in Dover Roade and further advise to carry the said shipp about by the Kings Channell in case the said Revolted shipps were in the Downes" (HCA 13/61 f.260v)

column17: LADING AT BARBADOS: TOBACCO "The said Daniel Kendall and Hugh Browne and  their company mentioned in the schedule arlate did in or about the moneth of July 1646 lade the severall quantities and parcells of tobacco expressed in the said schedule on board the said shippe in the Roade of the Isle of Barbadoes commonly called Carlisle Rode within the Jurisdiction of the Admiralty of England then said shipp then riding at anchor there" (HCA 13/61 f.2v); "In the judgement and estimtation of him this deponent and by the noates which hee soe tooke as before of the lading of the said severall  parcells of tobacco on board the said shipp the John, the said severall parcells did ioyntly and in the whole amount to the quantitie of one hundred and fiftie thousand pound weight of tobacco or neare thereabouts. And hee saieth that each and every pound of the said tobacco at the time of the bringing of the same into the port of Corke aforesaid both in the said port of Corke and Kingsale ws worth in the iudgement of this deponent and in common estimacon the summe of one shillinge lawfull English money one pound with another" (HCA 13/61 f.3v0: "The voyage aforesaid the mariners of the said shipp the John did putt and lade on board her for theire owne use and accompt severall parcells and rolles of tobacco contayning in all the quantitie of betweene twenty and thirty thousand pound weight of tobacco which hee knoweth because hee sawe the same laden and tooke accompt thereof" (HCA 13/61 f.4r)
column18: "Which hee knoweth because hee this deponent was acquainted with the charter partie and bills of lading at the time of their making and giving" (HCA 13/61 f.2v); "Which this deponent knoweth to be true, because having nowe seene and persued the said schedule, hee findeth it to agree in every particular with his bookes and notes which hee then tooke in the said Roade at such lading of the said tobacco, hee this deponent being then purser of the said shipp hee saith hee ws ordered and imployed by the said Captaine to take notice of the severll prcells and quantities of tobaccoes then laden on board and to sett the same downe inw riting and by whom or on whose accompt the same were soe respectively laden" (HCA 13/61 f.2v); "Hee had noe tobaccoes nor other goods saving his wearing clothes instruments writings and bookes on board the said shipp the John at the time of her taking as aforesaid"  (HCA 13/61 f.2v); "Hee sawe all the particular goods interrate laden and putt on board the said shipp the John in the roade aforesaid, which hee saith hee entred particularly downe in his booke by order of the said Captaine Parr and the master, and saith the particulars and markes were as is mentioned in the said schedules libellate" (HCA 13/61 f.2v); "Hee this deponent was on board and was acquainted with the said severall bills of lading soe given by the said Captaine Parr and alsoe with the said generll bill soe given by the said Mabbett hee this deponent hel;ping the said Mabbett to make his accompts thereabouts and to perfect the same by the bookes and notes which hee this deponent had soe as before taken at the lading of the said goods" (HCA 13/61 f.3r);  "In his booke hee tooke particular notice of all the said goods and to whom they did belonge and with what markes they were marked, and where they were consigned" (HCA 13/61 f.3r); "About the space of six weekes before the taking of the said shipp the John by the articulate Captaine Downes (which happened on or about the 12th of October 1646) and before her arrivall on the coasts of Ireland hee the said Captaine Parr called together all the pssengers and planters on board to whom hee had given any bill or bills of lading, and demannding to see the said bills hee the said Captaine Parr tooke bck into his hands the foresaid bills of lding soe s before by him  signed and given for every of the said severall quantities of tobacco soe laden on board, and with the consent of the said passengers and laders hee cancelled and made voide the same, And with their generll consent and agreement hee gave them other bills of lading for the delivery of the said goods schedulate in the ports of West Chester, Liverpoole or London derry" (HCA 13/61 f.3r); "By the order of Mr Vassall their owner hee carried over an order from the Committee of the Lords and Commons of the Admiraltie into Ireland to serve on the interrate Captaine Pluncket to appeare here in England, but hee did not serve the same upon him" (HCA 13/61 f.4r); "Hee sawe Captaine Parr signe all the sverall bills of lading for the goods in question, and sawe the said master signe a generall bill of lading to the said Captaine Parr" (HCA 13/61 ff.4v-5r)

column17: LADING AT DANZIG: CORN "The corne and graine arlate was measured on shore at Danske before it was brought aboard the said shipp, but was not measured into the shipp by the shipp side, nor on bord her when it was first laden, for hee saith if it had bin there measured, hee this deponent must needs have seene it in measuring, hee being on bord all the while it was taking in and stoweing" (HCA 13/61 f.18v)
column19: "The corne and graine arlate was measured on shore at Danske before it was brought aboard the said shipp, but was not measured into the shipp by the shipp side, nor on bord her when it was first laden, for hee saith if it had bin there measured, hee this deponent must needs have seene it in measuring, hee being on bord all the while it was taking in and stoweing" (HCA 13/61 f.18v); "The said corne and graine was brought abord the said shipp in Dansike vessells called Burthens, and that while the greatest part thereof was soe brought abord it was very stormy and tempestuous weather, soe that much of the said corne while it was heaving out of the said Burthens into the shipp fell by the side of the shipp and was lost in the sea, but of what quantitie the corne that was soe lost in the sea was hee saith hee knoweth not" (HCA 13/61 f.18v); "Their gunner William Bowell was by the said Plover sent ashore and imployed to see the corne and pease measured before the same came abord, and some other of the company did fetch the said corne on board" (HCA 13/61 f.19r); "By the said master's appointment their boatswaine Samuel Hawkins went up with the lighters to London with the said corne after it was laden into the said lighters out of the said shipp to see the same measured in this porte of London, whoe had in charge to looke to and have a care of it that none was imbeazeald"  (HCA 13/61 f.19r);

column18: "On or about the sixth day of March last past ut tempus recolit hee this deponent was present at the house of John Hiron a cooke situat in Gracious street London and knowne by the signe of the Pewter Platter there, (in which house this deponent is a servant) and did see the arlate John Mare with his owne hand subscribe, sale and for his act and deade deliver the said schedule, which being soe donne, hee this deponent and Robert Sun a scrivener did then and there sett their names thereto as witnesses, as now appeareth, this deponent having nowe seene and acknowledged his name thereto subscribed to be by him written the time and place aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.91v)

column17: LADING AT DANZIG: WHEAT "On or about the last  day of the said moneth of October last or frirst day of November alast past English stile (the time otherwise hee doth not nowe remember) they began to take in their ladinge of wheate on board the said shipp at Dantzicke, and that the quantitie of wheate they tooke in the first daye of their lading was 9 lasts and 17 sheyles or thereabouts, And further saith that jhaving taken  all her lading of wheate on board on the fifth day of the said moneth of November, and being cleared this deponent being ready to come on board her shee was (as hee saith) on the tenthd ay of the said moneth of November (being Friday) about nine of the clock in the forenoone by stresse of weather and violent stormes cast away and utterly lost in the Road of Dantzicke aforesaid" (HCA 13/61 f.510r)
